<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-01-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-01-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="1230" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1230">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.512/538.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Canada</persName> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Vera Cruz</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-01-11">
                                    <hi rend="italic">January 11, 1915</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Department’s December 24.<note n="71" xml:id="d1230fn71">
                                <ref target="frus1914#pg_784">Id. 784</ref>.</note> Foreign Office
                            transmits communication Vera Cruz State Governor in which he manifests
                            surprise that foreign oil companies ask protection when they are aiding
                            rebels, alleging some of the stockholders in arms against Government,
                            notwithstanding latter’s efforts to establish order. Before protecting
                            companies, it would be necessary to make them account for conduct,
                            punishing them for hostility.</p>
                        <p>No reason given for requiring companies to make second payment of
                            taxes.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Canada.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>